  "prompt": "What is the sense of smell?",
  "response": "The sense of smell, also known as olfaction, is the ability to detect and identify chemical molecules in the air through specialized organs called olfactory receptors located in the nasal cavity. When odor molecules enter the nose, they bind to these receptors, which then send signals to the olfactory bulb in the brain. The olfactory bulb processes these signals and sends them to other brain areas, including the olfactory cortex, where the perception of smell is generated.\n\nThe sense of smell plays a crucial role in various functions, including detecting hazards (like smoke or spoiled food), enjoying flavors (since aroma contributes significantly to taste), and forming memories and emotional experiences. \n\nHumans have a relatively moderate sense of smell, compared to some other animals such as dogs, who have a highly developed olfactory system.",
